{
  "A buffer solution resists changes in pH when small amounts of which substances are added?": "",
  "Only acids": "",
  "Only bases": "",
  "Both acids and bases": "",
  "Only neutral salts": "",
  "A buffer solution resists pH changes when small amounts of either acid or base are added. It does this through the equilibrium between a weak acid and its conjugate base (or a weak base and its conjugate acid).": "",
  "Which combination forms a buffer solution?": "",
  "HCl and NaOH": "",
  "HCl and NaCl": "",
  "CH3COOH and CH3COONa": "",
  "NaOH and NaCl": "",
  "A buffer consists of a weak acid and its conjugate base (or a weak base and its conjugate acid). Acetic acid (CH3COOH) and sodium acetate (CH3COONa) form a classic buffer pair. Strong acid/strong base combinations do not form buffers.": "",
  "The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation is pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]). When [A-] = [HA], the pH equals:": "",
  "7.00": "",
  "0": "",
  "pKa": "",
  "pKb": "",
  "When [A-] = [HA], the ratio [A-]/[HA] = 1, and log(1) = 0. So pH = pKa + 0 = pKa. This is why a buffer is most effective at a pH equal to the pKa of the weak acid.": "",
  "A buffer has the greatest capacity to resist pH changes when:": "",
  "The pH is far from the pKa": "",
  "The weak acid concentration is much greater than the conjugate base": "",
  "The solution is very dilute": "",
  "The concentrations of the weak acid and conjugate base are both high and roughly equal": "",
  "Buffer capacity is greatest when the concentrations of the weak acid and conjugate base are both high (providing more neutralizing capacity) and approximately equal (ensuring the buffer can handle both acid and base additions equally well).": "",
  "When a small amount of strong acid is added to a buffer solution containing HA and A-, what happens?": "",
  "The pH drops dramatically": "",
  "The H+ ions react with A- to form HA, minimizing pH change": "",
  "The H+ ions react with HA to form H2A": "",
  "The A- concentration increases": "",
  "When strong acid (H+) is added to a buffer, the conjugate base (A-) reacts with the H+ to form the weak acid (HA): A- + H+ -> HA. This consumes the added acid, preventing a large pH drop.": "",
  "A buffer is generally effective within what pH range relative to its pKa?": "",
  "pKa +/- 1": "",
  "pKa +/- 3": "",
  "pKa +/- 0.5": "",
  "pKa +/- 2": "",
  "A buffer is generally effective within +/- 1 pH unit of the pKa of the weak acid. Beyond this range, the ratio of [A-]/[HA] becomes too extreme (greater than 10:1 or less than 1:10) and the buffer can no longer resist pH changes effectively.": "",
  "Which of the following is NOT a buffer system?": "",
  "H2PO4- and HPO4^2-": "",
  "NH3 and NH4Cl": "",
  "H2CO3 and NaHCO3": "",
  "HCl is a strong acid, so HCl and NaCl do not form a buffer. A buffer requires a weak acid/conjugate base pair or a weak base/conjugate acid pair. All other options contain weak acid-conjugate base pairs.": "",
  "When a small amount of NaOH is added to a buffer of NH3/NH4+, what reaction occurs?": "",
  "NaOH has no effect on this buffer": "",
  "OH- reacts with H2O to form H3O+ and O2-": "",
  "OH- reacts with NH4+ to form NH3 and H2O": "",
  "OH- reacts with NH3 to form NH2- and H2O": "",
  "When OH- (from NaOH) is added to an NH3/NH4+ buffer, the OH- reacts with the conjugate acid NH4+: NH4+ + OH- -> NH3 + H2O. This consumes the added base, preventing a large pH increase.": "",
  "The blood buffer system primarily uses which pair?": "",
  "H2SO4 / HSO4-": "",
  "NaOH / Na+": "",
  "HCl / Cl-": "",
  "H2CO3 / HCO3-": "",
  "The primary buffer system in blood is the carbonic acid/bicarbonate (H2CO3/HCO3-) system. It maintains blood pH at approximately 7.4, which is critical for proper enzyme function and oxygen transport.": "",
  "If you need to prepare a buffer at pH 9.25, which weak acid/conjugate base pair would be most appropriate? (Ka values: acetic acid = 1.8 x 10^-5, NH4+ = 5.6 x 10^-10, HCN = 6.2 x 10^-10)": "",
  "NH4+/NH3 (pKa = 9.25)": "",
  "HCN/CN- (pKa = 9.21)": "",
  "Acetic acid/acetate (pKa = 4.74)": "",
  "Any of these would work equally well": "",
  "A buffer is most effective when pH = pKa. The NH4+/NH3 system has pKa = 9.25, which exactly matches the target pH. While HCN/CN- (pKa = 9.21) is close, NH4+/NH3 is the better choice since its pKa matches precisely.": "",
  "What does the term 'buffer capacity' mean?": "",
  "The pH at which the buffer operates": "",
  "The amount of strong acid or base a buffer can absorb before its pH changes significantly": "",
  "The volume of the buffer solution": "",
  "The pKa of the weak acid in the buffer": "",
  "Buffer capacity is a quantitative measure of how much strong acid or strong base can be added to a buffer solution before the pH changes by a significant amount (typically more than 1 unit). Higher concentrations of the buffer components increase buffer capacity.": "",
  "What does the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation describe?": "",
  "The relationship between pH, pKa, and the ratio of conjugate base to weak acid concentrations": "",
  "The total concentration of all species in a buffer": "",
  "The relationship between temperature and pH": "",
  "The rate at which buffers neutralize acids": "",
  "The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation, pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]), relates the pH of a buffer solution to the pKa of the weak acid and the ratio of the concentrations of the conjugate base [A-] to the weak acid [HA].": "",
  "What does the term 'conjugate acid-base pair' mean?": "",
  "Two substances with the same Ka value": "",
  "Any acid and base that react together": "",
  "Two substances that differ by one proton (H+)": "",
  "A strong acid paired with a strong base": "",
  "A conjugate acid-base pair consists of two species that differ by exactly one proton (H+). For example, CH3COOH (acetic acid) and CH3COO- (acetate ion) are a conjugate pair; the acid has one more H+ than its conjugate base.": "",
  "What does 'pKa' mean?": "",
  "The concentration of H+ ions in a 1 M acid solution": "",
  "The pH at which an acid is completely dissociated": "",
  "The negative base-10 logarithm of the acid dissociation constant Ka": "",
  "The percentage of acid molecules that ionize": "",
  "pKa = -log(Ka), where Ka is the acid dissociation constant. A smaller pKa indicates a stronger acid (larger Ka, greater tendency to donate protons), while a larger pKa indicates a weaker acid.": "",
  "What does the term 'common ion effect' mean in the context of buffer solutions?": "",
  "The shift in equilibrium that occurs when a salt containing an ion common to the weak electrolyte is added": "",
  "The increase in dissociation when more water is added": "",
  "The effect of temperature on equilibrium": "",
  "The precipitation that occurs when two ionic solutions are mixed": "",
  "The common ion effect describes the suppression of ionization of a weak electrolyte when a strong electrolyte sharing a common ion is added. For example, adding sodium acetate (which provides CH3COO-) to acetic acid suppresses its ionization, a principle central to how buffers work.": "",
  "What does the term 'buffer range' mean?": "",
  "The concentration range of the weak acid component": "",
  "The total volume of buffer that can be prepared": "",
  "The pH range over which a buffer effectively resists pH changes, typically pKa +/- 1": "",
  "The range of temperatures at which a buffer works": "",
  "The buffer range is the pH interval over which the buffer effectively maintains pH stability. This is typically within +/- 1 pH unit of the pKa of the weak acid, corresponding to a [A-]/[HA] ratio between 0.1 and 10.": "",
  "What does the phrase 'the buffer has been overwhelmed' mean?": "",
  "The temperature has exceeded the buffer's effective range": "",
  "So much acid or base has been added that one buffer component is essentially consumed, and the buffer can no longer resist pH changes": "",
  "The buffer solution has become too concentrated": "",
  "The buffer has been diluted to the point where its pH changes": "",
  "A buffer is overwhelmed when enough strong acid or base is added to essentially consume one of its components (either the weak acid or its conjugate base). Once one component is depleted, the solution can no longer resist pH changes and behaves like a simple acid or base solution.": "",
  "What does 'physiological buffer' mean?": "",
  "A buffer system that operates in living organisms to maintain pH within a narrow range necessary for life": "",
  "A buffer used only in medical laboratories": "",
  "A buffer that only works at room temperature": "",
  "A buffer made exclusively from organic compounds": "",
  "A physiological buffer is a buffer system that functions within a living organism. The carbonic acid/bicarbonate system in blood, the phosphate buffer system in cells, and the protein buffer system are all examples that maintain the narrow pH ranges required for biological processes.": "",
  "What does the term 'alkalosis' mean in the context of blood buffering?": "",
  "A condition where blood pH falls below 7.35": "",
  "A condition where blood pH is exactly 7.40": "",
  "A condition where the blood buffer is overwhelmed by acid": "",
  "A condition where blood pH rises above 7.45": "",
  "Alkalosis is a medical condition in which blood pH rises above the normal range of 7.35-7.45. It can be caused by hyperventilation (respiratory alkalosis) or excess bicarbonate (metabolic alkalosis). The opposite condition, acidosis, occurs when blood pH drops below 7.35.": "",
  "What does the term 'acidosis' mean in the context of blood buffering?": "",
  "A condition where blood pH drops below 7.35": "",
  "A condition where lactic acid is produced during exercise": "",
  "A condition where the stomach produces too much acid": "",
  "Acidosis is a condition in which the blood pH falls below the normal range of 7.35-7.45. It can result from excess CO2 buildup (respiratory acidosis) or accumulation of metabolic acids like lactic acid (metabolic acidosis). Both types can be life-threatening if severe.": "",
  "A biochemist needs to prepare a buffer at pH 5.00 using acetic acid (Ka = 1.8 x 10^-5, pKa = 4.74) and sodium acetate. What should the ratio of [CH3COO-]/[CH3COOH] be?": "",
  "1.00": "",
  "2.50": "",
  "0.55": "",
  "1.82": "",
  "Using Henderson-Hasselbalch: 5.00 = 4.74 + log([A-]/[HA]). log([A-]/[HA]) = 0.26. [A-]/[HA] = 10^0.26 = 1.82. The conjugate base must be at nearly twice the concentration of the weak acid to achieve pH 5.00.": "",
  "A student prepares a buffer by mixing 100.0 mL of 0.200 M acetic acid with 100.0 mL of 0.150 M sodium acetate (pKa = 4.74). What is the pH of this buffer?": "",
  "4.92": "",
  "4.74": "",
  "5.00": "",
  "4.62": "",
  "After mixing, moles HA = 0.200 x 0.100 = 0.0200 mol, moles A- = 0.150 x 0.100 = 0.0150 mol. pH = 4.74 + log(0.0150/0.0200) = 4.74 + log(0.75) = 4.74 + (-0.125) = 4.62. The pH is below 4.74 because there is more weak acid than conjugate base.": "",
  "A hospital pharmacist prepares a phosphate buffer (H2PO4-/HPO4^2-, pKa2 = 7.20) for an IV solution at pH 7.40. She has 0.100 M NaH2PO4 and 0.100 M Na2HPO4. What volume ratio of Na2HPO4 to NaH2PO4 should she use?": "",
  "0.63 : 1.00": "",
  "1.58 : 1.00": "",
  "2.00 : 1.00": "",
  "1.00 : 1.00": "",
  "Using Henderson-Hasselbalch: 7.40 = 7.20 + log([HPO4^2-]/[H2PO4-]). log(ratio) = 0.20, so ratio = 10^0.20 = 1.58. Since both stock solutions are the same concentration (0.100 M), the volume ratio of Na2HPO4 to NaH2PO4 is 1.58:1.00.": "",
  "A researcher adds 0.010 mol of HCl to 1.00 L of a buffer containing 0.100 mol CH3COOH and 0.100 mol CH3COO- (pKa = 4.74). What is the new pH?": "",
  "4.65": "",
  "2.00": "",
  "4.83": "",
  "The HCl reacts with A-: 0.010 mol H+ converts 0.010 mol A- to HA. New moles: A- = 0.100 - 0.010 = 0.090 mol; HA = 0.100 + 0.010 = 0.110 mol. pH = 4.74 + log(0.090/0.110) = 4.74 + log(0.818) = 4.74 - 0.087 = 4.65. The pH changed by only 0.09 units, demonstrating the buffer's effectiveness.": "",
  "A student has two buffer solutions, both at pH 4.74. Buffer A contains 1.00 M acetic acid and 1.00 M sodium acetate. Buffer B contains 0.010 M acetic acid and 0.010 M sodium acetate. Which has greater buffer capacity?": "",
  "Neither; buffer capacity depends only on pKa": "",
  "Buffer A, because it has higher concentrations of both buffer components": "",
  "Buffer B, because it is more dilute": "",
  "They have equal buffer capacity because they have the same pH": "",
  "Buffer capacity depends on the total concentrations of the buffer components, not just the pH. Buffer A has 100 times more moles of both acetic acid and acetate ion per liter, so it can neutralize 100 times more strong acid or base before its pH changes significantly.": "",
  "A biologist is studying an enzyme that functions optimally at pH 7.4. During a reaction, the enzyme produces 0.005 mol of H+ ions in 500 mL of a buffer containing 0.050 mol NaH2PO4 and 0.050 mol Na2HPO4 (pKa = 7.20). Will the buffer maintain the enzyme near its optimal pH?": "",
  "No, the pH will drop below 6.0": "",
  "No, the buffer will be overwhelmed": "",
  "Yes, the pH will change to approximately 7.02, still within a functional range": "",
  "Yes, the pH will not change at all": "",
  "The 0.005 mol H+ reacts with HPO4^2-: new HPO4^2- = 0.050 - 0.005 = 0.045 mol; new H2PO4- = 0.050 + 0.005 = 0.055 mol. pH = 7.20 + log(0.045/0.055) = 7.20 + log(0.818) = 7.20 - 0.087 = 7.11. This is close enough to pH 7.4 to keep the enzyme somewhat functional, though not ideal. The buffer prevented a catastrophic pH drop.": "",
  "A chemistry student wants to prepare 500 mL of an NH3/NH4Cl buffer at pH 9.50 (pKa of NH4+ = 9.25). If the total buffer concentration ([NH3] + [NH4+]) is to be 0.200 M, how many moles of each component are needed?": "",
  "0.036 mol NH3 and 0.064 mol NH4Cl": "",
  "0.080 mol NH3 and 0.020 mol NH4Cl": "",
  "0.050 mol NH3 and 0.050 mol NH4Cl": "",
  "0.064 mol NH3 and 0.036 mol NH4Cl": "",
  "Using Henderson-Hasselbalch: 9.50 = 9.25 + log([NH3]/[NH4+]). log(ratio) = 0.25, ratio = 10^0.25 = 1.78. Total moles = 0.200 x 0.500 = 0.100 mol. If [NH3] = 1.78x and [NH4+] = x, then 2.78x = 0.100, x = 0.036 mol NH4+. NH3 = 0.100 - 0.036 = 0.064 mol. So 0.064 mol NH3 and 0.036 mol NH4Cl are needed.": "",
  "An environmental scientist is analyzing lake water and finds it naturally buffered at pH 6.4 by the carbonic acid/bicarbonate system (H2CO3/HCO3-, pKa1 = 6.35). Acid rain adds 0.001 mol H+ per liter. If the lake's total buffer concentration is 0.002 M, what happens?": "",
  "The lake becomes more alkaline": "",
  "The buffer easily handles the acid rain with minimal pH change": "",
  "The buffer is overwhelmed because the acid added exceeds the buffer's capacity": "",
  "The pH rises above 7": "",
  "The total buffer concentration is only 0.002 M, meaning HCO3- is at most about 0.001 M (roughly half the total). Adding 0.001 mol/L of H+ would consume all the available HCO3-, overwhelming the buffer. The lake's buffering capacity is too low to handle this acid load, and the pH would drop significantly.": "",
  "A chemical engineer needs to maintain the pH of a fermentation tank at 4.00. She chooses between a formic acid buffer (HCOOH/HCOO-, pKa = 3.75) and a benzoic acid buffer (C6H5COOH/C6H5COO-, pKa = 4.20). Which is the better choice and why?": "",
  "Either buffer works equally well": "",
  "Benzoic acid, because its pKa (4.20) is closer to pH 4.00": "",
  "Neither buffer is appropriate for this pH": "",
  "Formic acid, because its pKa (3.75) is closer to pH 4.00": "",
  "Benzoic acid (pKa = 4.20) is only 0.20 pH units away from the target pH of 4.00, while formic acid (pKa = 3.75) is 0.25 units away. Both are within the effective buffer range (pKa +/- 1), but benzoic acid is the better choice because its pKa is closer to the target pH, providing greater buffer capacity at that pH.": "",
  "A patient with severe diarrhea loses large amounts of bicarbonate (HCO3-). Given that the blood buffer system is H2CO3/HCO3- (pKa = 6.10) and normal blood pH is 7.40, how does this loss affect blood pH and the [HCO3-]/[H2CO3] ratio?": "",
  "Blood pH increases; the ratio increases": "",
  "Blood pH increases; the ratio decreases": "",
  "Blood pH decreases; the [HCO3-]/[H2CO3] ratio decreases": "",
  "Blood pH stays the same; the body compensates immediately": "",
  "Loss of HCO3- decreases the numerator in the [HCO3-]/[H2CO3] ratio, which reduces the log term in the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation (pH = 6.10 + log([HCO3-]/[H2CO3])). A lower ratio means a lower pH, causing metabolic acidosis. The normal ratio is about 20:1; any decrease shifts blood pH downward.": ""
}